class Solution {
public:
    int maximumElementAfterDecrementingAndRearranging(vector<int>& arr) {

        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());

        arr[0] = 1;

        for (int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {

            arr[i] = min(arr[i], arr[i - 1] + 1);
        }

        return arr.back();
    }
};

Approach
First, I sort the array in increasing order.

Then I set the first element to 1 because the problem requires it.

Now I go through the remaining elements one by one.

For each element, there are two possibilities:

If it is already small enough, I keep it.
If it is too large, I decrease it to previous + 1.
So the new value becomes:

arr[i] = min(arr[i], arr[i - 1] + 1)

This guarantees two things:

The array always satisfies the adjacent difference condition.
Every element is as large as possible, so the last element becomes the maximum possible answer.
Finally, I return the last element of the array.

